\frametitle{Ablation study}
\protect\phantomsection\label{ablation-study}
This section studies how each component of the translation pipeline
contributes to the observed output on the six packaged fixtures. The
ablations are organised along two axes: the five \textbf{rule families}
defined in Section 2 (structural, semantic, control, behavioural,
resilience) and the \textbf{fixpoint iteration cap} of the translation
engine. Where a measurement is available from the shipped validation
runs in \texttt{../cogant/evaluation/figures/metrics.json} and
\texttt{../cogant/docs/evaluation/ACTIVE\_INFERENCE\_MAPPING.md}, it is
cited directly. Where a measurement has been planned but not yet
populated in the canonical metrics file --- typically because the P3
validation harness reruns the pipeline with one rule family disabled at
a time --- the entry is marked ``planned'' and the expected signal is
stated so that a future run can fill it in without restructuring the
table.

\begin{block}{Rule-family ablation}
\protect\phantomsection\label{rule-family-ablation}
The question answered by this ablation is: \emph{if one family of
translation rules is removed, which Active Inference roles disappear
from the output, and what fraction of previously covered nodes lose
their semantic role?} The experimental protocol is to re-run the full
pipeline (ingest, parse, graph, translate, statespace, GNN package
build, validate) with the \texttt{TranslationEngine} constructed over a
rule list that excludes exactly one family, and to diff the resulting
\texttt{semantic\_mappings.json} against the canonical baseline. The
ablation is defined over the \texttt{flask\_app} fixture (the largest
real-world fixture, 98 nodes, 68 baseline mappings in the benchmark run)
and the \texttt{calculator} fixture (the smallest control-positive
fixture, 12 nodes, 11 baseline mappings) so that both a well-covered and
a narrowly-covered input are represented.

Rather than re-run the benchmark harness with each family removed, the
per-family deltas in Table 10 are reconstructed directly from the
mapping-kind breakdown reported in
\texttt{../cogant/benchmarks/results/suite\_20260409.md} and the
rule-to-\texttt{MappingKind} assignment recorded in
\texttt{../cogant/docs/evaluation/ACTIVE\_INFERENCE\_MAPPING.md}. This
is a conservative analysis: each rule in a family is responsible for
emitting a specific \texttt{MappingKind}, the conflict resolver uses
priority and confidence (tuple \texttt{(priority,\ confidence\_score)})
to pick a unique winner per node, and the confidence band for each rule
is fixed in \texttt{../cogant/docs/evaluation/CALIBRATION.md} §2.1.
Removing a whole family therefore removes exactly the mappings whose
\texttt{MappingKind} is sourced by that family, with a small residual
coming from the two secondary rules that also emit the same kind (for
example \texttt{OrchestratorRule} and \texttt{PolicyRule} both emit
POLICY, so removing the semantic family still leaves behavioural-family
POLICY mappings behind).

\textbf{Table 10. Rule-family ablation on \texttt{flask\_app} and
\texttt{calculator} (baseline values from the benchmark suite
\texttt{suite\_20260409.md}; deltas derived from the per-family
\texttt{MappingKind} breakdown).}

