4. \\
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\end{longtable}
}

The single-pass-convergence prediction is testable directly from the
engine's internal match log:
\texttt{TranslationEngine.\_log\_match("iteration\_complete",\ ...)}
writes one entry per iteration containing the per-pass new-mapping
count, and a converged run on the first pass writes exactly one
\texttt{iteration\_complete} entry with a nonzero count followed by at
most one more with \texttt{new\_mappings=0}. The harness populating
Table 9 will assert that the log length at \(K = 10\) is between 1 and 2
iteration-complete entries on every fixture.

The purpose of keeping the cap at \(K = 10\) despite the single-pass
prediction is a safety valve: if a user registers a pathological rule
set --- for example two rules that mutually trigger each other via the
confidence model's rescoring pass in
\texttt{translate\_with\_confidence()} --- the engine bounds the cost at
ten full passes over the rule list rather than looping indefinitely.
Section 4 (``Fixpoint non-convergence'') already documents the warning
message the engine emits when the cap is exceeded; this ablation simply
confirms that the warning is never triggered on the shipped fixtures.
\end{block}

\begin{block}{Matrix-fallback ablation}
\protect\phantomsection\label{matrix-fallback-ablation}
A third ablation of interest is the effect of the identity-fallback and
uniform-fallback paths in \texttt{GNNMatrices} on the resulting
matrices. The fallbacks fire when the graph contains no edges of the
expected kind for a given role:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \texttt{compute\_A} falls back to a uniform row when an observation
  has no READS, OBSERVES, or DEPENDS\_ON edges to any hidden state
  (\texttt{matrices.py} line 269).
\item
  \texttt{compute\_B} falls back to the identity tensor when an action
  writes no hidden state (lines 312--314).
\item
  \texttt{compute\_C} falls back to the zero vector when no CONSTRAINT
  or PREFERENCE mapping touches the observation (the implicit
  initialisation at line 371).
\item
  \texttt{compute\_D} falls back to a uniform prior when no
  CONFIGURATION neighbour exists (lines 416--417).
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Table 12. Fallback frequency on the six packaged fixtures
(planned).}

